{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518497"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:05:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:05:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12930"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12930"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.11,0.11,0,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53130"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5368"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12930"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38555"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"3001"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15492"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53130"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with flank pain that developed while hiking in cold weather. He also noticed his fingertips turning purple. He has a medical history of a respiratory tract infection 11 months ago, a gastric ulcer one year ago for which he received an iron infusion, and hypercholestrolaemia. His only regular medication is simvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 120/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.2\u00b0C. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. His urinalysis shows very dark urine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 95 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaematocrit: 31.8% (41-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCV: 86 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 7.2 x 10^9/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count: 280 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral blood picture: clumping of red blood cells and frequent spherocytes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELDH: 450 U/L (140-280)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 68 \u00b5mol/L (60-115)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect Antiglobulin Test (Coombs Test): Positive for Complement (C3, C4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum Iron: 75 \u00b5g/dL (60-170)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum Ferritin: 60 ng/mL (12-150)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal Iron Binding Capacity: 350 \u00b5g/dL (250-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransferrin Saturation: 21% (20-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thalassaemia","Sickle cell anaemia","Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency","Iron deficiency anaemia","Autoimmune haemolytic anaemia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eautoimmune haemolytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically cold autoimmune haemolytic anaemia (AIHA). Cold AIHA is characterized by IgM autoantibodies that bind to erythrocyte I (or i) antigens at temperatures below 37\u00b0C, causing red cell agglutination and haemolysis. This explains the patient\u0027s symptoms occurring during cold exposure. The purple fingertips result from local red cell agglutination in acral areas, not true cyanosis. Flank pain can occur due to kidney involvement from haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey laboratory findings supporting this diagnosis include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Anaemia (Hb 95 g/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. Evidence of haemolysis (elevated LDH, dark urine)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Positive Direct Antiglobulin Test (Coombs Test) for complement (C3, C4), which is typical for cold AIHA\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E4. Peripheral blood picture showing red cell clumping and spherocytes\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s recent history of a respiratory tract infection is relevant, as cold AIHA can be triggered by infections, particularly with\u003Cem\u003E Mycoplasma pneumoniae.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESickle cell anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in this case. While it can cause severe pain, the peripheral blood smear would show sickle cells, which are not mentioned here. Additionally, sickle cell disease typically presents at a younger age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is typically triggered by specific medications or foods, not by cold exposure. The peripheral blood smear in G6PD deficiency would show bite cells, which are not mentioned here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThalassaemia\u003C/strong\u003E causes a microcytic, hypochromic anaemia, which is not seen in this patient\u0027s blood results (MCV is normal). The peripheral blood smear in thalassaemia would typically show target cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E does not fit this clinical picture. While the patient has a history of iron infusion, his current iron studies are normal. Moreover, iron deficiency does not explain the haemolysis (elevated LDH, dark urine) or the positive Coombs test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of cold-induced symptoms, evidence of haemolysis, and a positive Coombs test for complement makes cold autoimmune haemolytic anaemia the most likely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cold autoimmune haemolytic anaemia is characterized by IgM autoantibodies that bind to erythrocyte I (or i) antigens at temperatures below 37\u00b0C, causing red cell agglutination and haemolysis.","Acrocyanosis and flank pain can be presenting features of cold autoimmune haemolytic anaemia due to local red cell agglutination and haemolysis.","A positive Direct Antiglobulin Test (Coombs Test) for complement (C3, C4) is indicative of cold autoimmune haemolytic anaemia."],"references":["Barcellini W and Fattizzo B (2020) The Changing Landscape of Autoimmune Hemolytic Anemia. Front. Immunol. 11:946. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2020.00946"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38555"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12930"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38555"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-16T21:28:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-19T21:02:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5368"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53130"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[